hit_tag2_q: I learned that 58% of calories in American's diets come from ultra-processed foods.

hit_cue1_q: I learned that short, sporadic instances or exercise in a day benefit general physical and brain health. I knew that it benefits brain health a little bit by increasing the flow of oxygen to the brain. It makes me think of how I don't do much physical exercise, but when I do, I sometimes feel like air is rushing to my brain because I am not used to it. This information can be useful to people like me who don't exercise as much, and it makes me feel hopeful that I can still benefit my health in some way.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that 58% of calories in Americans' diets come from ultra-processed foods. I figured that Americans' diets would consist of a lot of processed foods because that is what is cheap and accessible to most people. The information makes me think about how the US has high rates of obesity, so knowing about ultra-processed foods versus natural foods such as fruits and vegetables is extremely important. It is especially important for low-income people and families to know how to support the health of their family members better. This information makes me feel irritated that accessibility to healthier foods is lacking, and that we need to do a better job of lowering prices so people can have these things.
hit_cue3_q: The point of self monitoring food intake is to show yourself how much of what specific nutrient or number of calories you have eaten so you can better plan for the future.​​​​​​​ The information makes me think about my own health and how I don't really keep track of what I eat. This information can be helpful for individuals like me, or for individuals that are specifically looking to lose or gain weight in a healthy way. It makes me feel hopeful for these people that have set goals in mind.
hit_cue4_q: I learned that you can calculate the Glycemic Load of food by multiplying the glycemic index by the number of carbs and dividing by 100. I knew how to calculate the number of carbohydrates in a specific food item, but not the glycemic load. This information can be especially important for individuals with diabetes who need to keep track of their sugar levels. This information makes me feelLike I can make a better informed decision about my glycemic intake.
hit_cue5_q: It is better to eat low density foods because they contain less calories but still satisfy hunger urges. Additionally this information makes me think about how again, most people do not have access to healthier food options due to financial situations. hit_cue1_q: I learned that vigorous exercise can reduce anxiety and improve sleep. I already knew this but it wasn't something I thought much about. However it did make me look at and think about how little exercise I do get, and that I should probably do more. I am encouraged by the information that states smaller bursts of exercise will do the job.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that 58% of my diet is likely to be ultra processed food. Again this is knowledge I had, but the amounts of processed foods shocked me a little. I guess I am just not as aware of it as I thought I was. This makes me think I should pay more attention, and take action to reduce some of these foods from my diet. I feel a little bit betrayed by the food industry when I see how vast the industry is.
hit_cue3_q: I learned that monitoring food intake is like keeping a financial budget.​​​​​​​ I have tried self monitoring a few times but it was pretty boring. But when I saw it compared to budgeting I thought well hello! For some reason that must makes so much better sense. I think that information makes self monitoring more relatable when compared to something so cut and dried like money. I feel more alert and aware haviong made this connection. It feels fresh.
hit_cue4_q: I learned that table sugar has a GI of 100. I am aware of the term glycemic index, but not of the ranges, or of what foods are low or high. When reading these ranges I thought that lows would be unprocessed veggies, mediums may be fruits or other naturally sweeter foods, and that highs are going to be the ultra processed foods. I think this information is good to be aware of while shopping in particular, and in meal planning. This article was very dry and dull but it did, with some effort, make me feel a little more educated and aware of my surroundings.
hit_cue5_q: I learned that low energy foods will make us full with fewer calories. It seems like common sense, but it helps to have it pointed out. When I read this passage, I had thoughts of cauliflower and chocolate, and how if only cauliflower tasted as good and satisfied cravings like chocolate did. This is good information though, for controlling calorie consumption without starving yourself. I feel like I should eat more cauliflower, so a little guilty I guess.
hit_cue6_q: I learned that people consume less calories when they eat the same thing every day.​ My grandfather ate oatmeal for breakfast every day as long as I knew him. He was a fit man, so perhaps it’s true. I was thinking about him when I read this information. By balancing the same foods, with a wide variety of different foods, and paying to the energy values of each type, you can control your calories easily. I feel like I do not pay attention to food, nor do I want to, but I have to, otherwise I’ll be taken advantage of buy companies making highly processed high energy foods. This is depressing.​​​​​​
hit_cue7_q: I learned that strengthening exercises can reduce insulin resistance. I didn’t realize exercise was more than burning calories and increasing strength and flexibility. I think that as time passes, it becomes more and more important to somehow find a way to perceive exercise as less unpleasant. This information may encourage people to exercise. I feel like it’s possible. Uplifted.

hit_tag2_q: Ultra-processed foods can lead to over consumption of calories because you don't feel full.
hit_tag3_q: Self-Monitoring such as food intake apps can help you keep an eye on the food you are consuming.
hit_tag4_q: The glycemic index can help you keep track of glucose levels in food.
hit_tag5_q: Consuming lower density foods will allow you to feel fuller.
hit_tag6_q: Having a variety of low density foods will help keep your interest and help you feel full.

hit_cue1_q: You don't need to work out for long periods of time if you don't feel like it. Small amounts of exercise can help to improve brain health. By doing strengthening exercises in smaller increments it will also help to maintain your general health. Exercise is beneficial to the mind and body and it really doesn't have to take up that much time in your day.
hit_cue2_q: Ultra-processed foods can lead to over consumption of calories because you don't feel full. By eliminating processed foods you can free up more space in your diet for healthier snack options.
hit_cue3_q: Self-Monitoring food intake apps can help you keep an eye on the food you are consuming.​​​​​​​ By tracking the foods you consume, you can understand and make adjustments to help assist in your health journey.
hit_cue4_q: The glycemic index can help you keep track of glucose levels in food. It can also help you understand which foods to avoid in order to make better choices for your mind and body.
hit_cue5_q: Consuming lower density foods will allow you to feel fuller. Higher density foods give a false sense of fulfillment.
hit_cue6_q: Having a variety of low density foods will help keep your interest and help you feel full. Variety is important in helping you expand your healthy eating habits.​​​​​​​
hit_cue7_q: Strengthening exercises are helpful for building stronger muscles and bones, allowing for an easier time with activities.

hit_cue5: Consuming lower density foods will allow you to feel fuller. Higher density foods give a false sense of fulfillment.

hit_cue3_q: Monitoring your food intake helps you make better choices in the future​​​​​​​.  When I have tracked my calories, weight, steps, etc., I was more mindful of what I ate and I lost weight. hit_cue4_q: There are foods that have a small effect on blood glucose. It made me think about the foods that do the opposite that I know of.  I get low blood sugar so I thought of that. hit_cue5_q: You can feel fuller but lose weight by eating foods that have low energy density. I knew a little bit about this but not too much.  It made me think that I need to learn more about this. hit_cue6_q: Give yourself a variety of healthy foods to help you lose weight without feeling bored.​​​​​​​ I know dieting can be boring because there are limits. I felt like this could give me motivation to continue doing the diet I need to start.

hit_cue1_q: I learned that after physical activity, people experience less anxiety and have improved sleep. I already knew this information despite not being able to do much physical activity for myself. It's also written in a very simplified way that suggests no other occurring health issues at play which makes it not worthwhile for a sizable portion of the population.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that around 58% of the calories in an average American diet comes from ultra-processed foods. I didn't know the specific number but I assumed at least half of the diet was processed foods. Again, the way this information is presented is very simplified because it assumes that everyone has access to healthy, unprocessed foods which is not the reality. People living in food deserts or are too poor to afford unprocessed foods do not benefit from being told the negative impacts of ultra processed foods.
hit_cue3_q: I learned that the goal of self monitoring is to increase awareness of behaviors that lead to weight loss​​​​​​​. This paragraph was the least useful to me and made me the most annoyed out of all of them. This kind of behavior can be very dangerous to some people and lead to eating disorders. While some people may be able to keep a food diary and track calories, many people including myself, cannot do that without slipping into a very unhealthy mindset of restrictive eating.
hit_cue4_q: I learned that GI refers to how much eating a certain food might change your blood glucose levels. Again, this information is useful for those who have the means to buy healthier foods. I knew already that some foods can increase blood sugar much more than others. It made me frustrated to think about how so many people simply can't afford to focus on things like this because they are just trying to survive.
hit_cue5_q: I learned that the physical space the food takes up in our stomach is a big contributor to our fullness level. I think there is value in being able to feel when you get full but I also understand that some people are less in tune with their body in that way which makes this challenging for them. I didn't know about the "traffic light eating plan" but the idea of it sounds better on paper than I would imagine it words in practice.
hit_cue6_q: I learned that people tend to consume less calories when there is less variety in the food​​​​​​​. While the logic of this is sound, it wouldn't work for everyone. Some people, such as some autistic people with sensory issues, have no problems eating the same foods over and over. Any kind of change in diet should be tailor made to the individual because broad one-size-fits-all diets simply do not work for most people. It annoys me when information is portrayed in a way to suggest that everyone can benefit from it when that simply isn't the case.
hit_cue7_q: I learned that strength training can help lower blood pressure and has other positive health effects. I know strength training is useful and it can help lots of people, especially those at risk of developing diabetes. The last sentence of this paragraph was the best one because it actually advises people to listen to their body.

hit_cue1_q: I learned that brief episodes of activity can improve cognitive function like memory and the ability to plan. This information is similar to what I already knew was helpful for a general, mostly-healthy population. However I also know that this information is not helpful for persons with certain medical conditions for whom exercise - and even cognitive exercise - can be detrimental to their overall health and cognitive abilities in the short-or-medium-length terms after the exercise is completed. So this information is useful for many people, but a little frustrating for myself & others for whom it does not apply.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that more than half of the calories in the average American diet come from ultra-processed foods. This information is likely useful for people who have not spent a lot of time examining their diet and are interested in learning to eat healthier and, perhaps, lose a little weight. I feel like this paragraph is trending a little towards the idea that some foods are good and some are bad (though it is not specifically stated in such a way) and this framing can be problematic for those with disordered eating. I mostly was thinking about how there is no one set diet or food that is healthy for everyone because people have individual medical and health needs.
hit_cue3_q: I learned that whoever wrote this paragraph thinks that calorie counting and monitoring weight measurements are vital to the goal of weight loss.​​​​​​​ I was honestly a little annoyed reading this section, as I find that in many cases obsession with food choices and weight as measurements of health does not actually help people become healthier or lose weight. Nor should we necessarily assume that losing weight is a required element of gaining health. But this information could be useful to people who are wanting to learn more about their body and how to balance their food habits with their exercise habits in safe ways, or simply to learn more about their personal habits around food and exercise.
hit_cue4_q: I learned how to calculate the glycemic load of a meal or snack. Prior to this paragraph I already knew some basics about the glycemic index. This information is interesting, but I don't think it necesarily provides value to the average person who isn't dealing with blood sugar or similar issues.
hit_cue5_q: I learned that something called the Traffic Light Eating Plan is based around tricking the body/person into thinking they are fuller by eating foods that take up a lot of space but don't have a lot of calories. I am inherently skeptical of most weight loss plans, especially ones that come with cute little names, especially when I am not provided any background informaton on who created the plan and the research which supports it's use. I do think it's helpful to know what types of foods make you feel full without adding unnecessary calories and think most people can benefit from this general knowledge.
hit_cue6_q: I learned that more variety of foods tends to encourage people to eat more.​​​​​​​ I found this fact to be interesting. The suggestion of increasing variety of some foods (especially ones people may be more reluctant to eat like vegetables) while decreasing variety of foods that taste good but aren't the healthiest for you to be something that could help a lot of people. It seems to be a more balanced approach than suggestions to simply restrict consumption of foods like sweets and fats, which many people understandably have trouble sticking with.
hit_cue7_q: I learned that muscle strengthening exercises are specifically recommended to diabetics by the American Diabetes Association. I actually would be interested in learning more about why specifically these types of exercises are considered beneficial for that patient population. This information, especially the part at the end about consistent practice and slowly increasing difficulty, could be useful for most relatively-healthy persons. However, once again I am thinking about how these types of exercise are not safe or recommended for some patient populations, and it could be helpful to acknowledge that the "slowly increase difficulty" recommendation is not feasible or appropriate for everyone. Some people will be better off sticking with the same simple exercises at the same level virtually indefinitely.

hit_cue1_q: I learned that even short periods of physical activity can affect cognitive function in a positive way. This was not something I was previously aware of and made me think about how I can incorporate short exercises into my daily life. This is useful for all people and makes me feel that exercising might be easier to approach than I previously thought.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that about half of the calories the average American consumes comes from ultra processed foods. I did not previously know this and made me think about the effects of this issue on the future of American society. This information is useful for all Americans to know and made me feel slightly fearful of the food industry.
hit_cue3_q: I learned that self-monitoring can increase my awareness of what my body is consuming.​ I felt that this was information that was fairly obvious and made me think about how this kind of behavior might feed into the prevalence of eating disorders. I think this information is useful for people trying to lose weight but made me feel worried about people who are unhealthily insecure about their weight.​​​​​​
hit_cue4_q: I learned that glycemic load is calculated by multiplying the glycemic index value of a food by the number of carbs in a serving and then dividing by 100. I did not previously know why this was important but made me think about diabetes. I think this information is useful for those at risk of blood sugar disorders. It did not make me feel any strong emotion.
hit_cue5_q: I learned that energy is basically calories. I did not realize that that was what calories were. I thought reading calories were simply a way to watch what you eat to lose weight. It made me think about the science of our bodies and how we consume energy. I think this information would be useful for everyone to know. This made me feel oddly positive.
hit_cue6_q: I learned that it is important to increase the variety of foods I eat.​​​​​​​ I felt that this was something I knew but I did not know the nutrition science behind this fact. It made me think about what I currently eat. I think this is useful for everyone to know and made me feel like I should start introducing more variety to what I eat.
hit_cue7_q: I learned that strengthening exercises should be done in regularly but with increasing difficulty of the exercises. I don't know how to exercise so this was good to know. hit_tag1_q: Physical activities in 10 minute increments has been proven to have an impact on peoples' health.
hit_tag2_q: Ultra-processed foods are easier to eat in larger quantity before feeling full, which makes it more difficult to stop eating when full or when we have consumed enough calories.
hit_tag3_q: Self-monitoring your caloric intake, exercise, and weight could help make you more aware your behavior and habits that you may not be aware of that could help you lose weight.
hit_tag4_q: Becoming more aware of the glycemic index could help monitor your glucose and A1C levels
hit_tag5_q: The Traffic Light Eating Plan is a plan filled mostly with vegetables, fruits and lean proteins, minimum dairy and fat.
hit_tag6_q: People have a tendency to eat more calories if they have access to a variety of foods versus when variety is reduced
hit_tag7_q: Lifting weights or strength training at least 3 times per week can result in better blood sugar control, reduced insulin resistance, decreased fat mass, lower blood pressure, and increased muscle strength.
hit_cue1_q: Physical activities in 10 minute increments has been proven to have an impact on peoples' health. I've always know that exercising improved sleep, that's from experience. It made me think about the days we cut grass, how well I sleep at night. This information would be most helpful for those who suffer with insomnia. The information makes me feel like I need to do more exercising especially on the days we don't cut grass.
hit_cue2_q: Ultra-processed foods are easier to eat in larger quantity before feeling full, which makes it more difficult to stop eating when full or when we have consumed enough calories. It is difficult to not eat processed foods simply because the majority of the American diet is processed. It made me think about finding sample meal plans that do not include ultra processed foods. This information is useful to all people who have digestive issues, diabetes, and other diseases. This information makes me feel like I need to be more attentive to what I am eating.
hit_cue3_q: Self-monitoring your caloric intake, exercise, and weight could help make you more aware your behavior and habits that you may not be aware of that could help you lose weight.​​​​​​​ I know it is helpful to self monitor, however, it is tedious even with apps. It made me think about how much time it takes to enter your meals. It also made me think about Spark People, which doesn't exist anymore. I loved the site because I didn't really have to enter too many foods as they had the menus already prepared for you to follow. Self monitoring takes a lot of time so I think about those who work who may not have time. It would be useful for those with diabetes, high blood pressure,, etc. so they can be more aware of what they are eating. It made me feel like being healthy takes a lot of work.
hit_cue4_q: Becoming more aware of the glycemic index could help monitor your glucose and A1C levels.  I already knew that the lower foods on the glycemic index were helpful in controlling blood sugar levels. It made me think about if you're able to control your blood sugar, you are able to get ahead of a lot of health issues. A lot of issues such as cholesterol and blood sugar levels, come from eating too many carbs and sugar. This information would be useful for those who want to prevent prediabetes, diabetes, high cholesterol, etc. The information made me feel like I need to be more aware of foods on the glycemic index in order to lower my A1C levels.
hit_cue5_q: The Traffic Light Eating Plan is a plan filled mostly with vegetables, fruits and lean proteins, minimum dairy and fat. I've always known that vegetables are important. My doctor has always advised me to attempt to eat at least 4 cups of vegetables per day. This is difficult for me since I usually don't have my first meal of the day until 12 or 1:00pm. It made me think about the advice my doctor always gives me of eating 4 cups of vegetables per day. This information would be useful for anyone who struggles with blood vessel issues and other diseases. All the information thus far made me feel overwhelmed by trying to remember all the different techniques.
hit_cue6_q: People have a tendency to eat more calories if they have access to a variety of foods versus when variety is reduced​​​​​​​. In my own personal experience, you always eat more when you go to a buffet than you would if you ordered a single meal. It made me think about how much we eat when we go to a buffet. This information is good for anyone who wants to make a change in order to improve their health. It made me feel like my option of going to a sit down meal/restaurant is better than going to a buffet or fast food.
hit_cue7_q: Lifting weights or strength training at least 3 times per week can result in better blood sugar control, reduced insulin resistance, decreased fat mass, lower blood pressure, and increased muscle strength.  I have weights and I knew they could help with weight control. I  have often thought about how many times I have put the weights beside the sofa so I could use them while I was sitting, but that did not help. This information is useful to anyone who wants to improve their health. It made me feel like I have the tools to improve my health but have not used them to do so.

It made me think about the days we cut grass, how well I sleep at night. This information would be most helpful for those who suffer with insomnia. The information makes me feel like I need to do more exercising especially on the days we don't cut grass.
hit_cue2: Ultra-processed foods are easier to eat in larger quantity before feeling full, which makes it more difficult to stop eating when full or when we have consumed enough calories. It is difficult to not eat processed foods simply because the majority of the American diet is processed. It made me think about finding sample meal plans that do not include ultra processed foods. This information is useful to all people who have digestive issues, diabetes, and other diseases. This information makes me feel like I need to be more attentive to what I am eating.
hit_cue3: Self-monitoring your caloric intake, exercise, and weight could help make you more aware your behavior and habits that you may not be aware of that could help you lose weight.​​​​​​​ I know it is helpful to self monitor, however, it is tedious even with apps. It made me think about how much time it takes to enter your meals. It also made me think about Spark People, which doesn't exist anymore. I loved the site because I didn't really have to enter too many foods as they had the menus already prepared for you to follow. Self monitoring takes a lot of time so I think about those who work who may not have time. It would be useful for those with diabetes, high blood pressure,, etc. so they can be more aware of what they are eating. It made me feel like being healthy takes a lot of work.
hit_cue4: Becoming more aware of the glycemic index could help monitor your glucose and A1C levels.  I already knew that the lower foods on the glycemic index were helpful in controlling blood sugar levels. It made me think about if you're able to control your blood sugar, you are able to get ahead of a lot of health issues. A lot of issues such as cholesterol and blood sugar levels, come from eating too many carbs and sugar. This information would be useful for those who want to prevent prediabetes, diabetes, high cholesterol, etc. The information made me feel like I need to be more aware of foods on the glycemic index in order to lower my A1C levels.
hit_cue5: The Traffic Light Eating Plan is a plan filled mostly with vegetables, fruits and lean proteins, minimum dairy and fat. I've always known that vegetables are important. My doctor has always advised me to attempt to eat at least 4 cups of vegetables per day. This is difficult for me since I usually don't have my first meal of the day until 12 or 1:00pm. It made me think about the advice my doctor always gives me of eating 4 cups of vegetables per day. This information would be useful for anyone who struggles with blood vessel issues and other diseases. All the information thus far made me feel overwhelmed by trying to remember all the different techniques.
hit_cue6: People have a tendency to eat more calories if they have access to a variety of foods versus when variety is reduced​​​​​​​. In my own personal experience, you always eat more when you go to a buffet than you would if you ordered a single meal. It made me think about how much we eat when we go to a buffet. This information is good for anyone who wants to make a change in order to improve their health. It made me feel like my option of going to a sit down meal/restaurant is better than going to a buffet or fast food.
hit_cue7: Lifting weights or strength training at least 3 times per week can result in better blood sugar control, reduced insulin resistance, decreased fat mass, lower blood pressure, and increased muscle strength.  I have weights and I knew they could help with weight control. I  have often thought about how many times I have put the weights beside the sofa so I could use them while I was sitting, but that did not help. This information is useful to anyone who wants to improve their health. It made me feel like I have the tools to improve my health but have not used them to do so.

hit_cue1_q: The information provided added to my understanding that it is more important to regularly move, even in small amounts, than to wait to do something vigorous and end up doing nothing. My instinct is an "all or nothing" mindset. As someone who lives with chronic pain, it isn't uncommon that I simply give up when I cannot make the full effort. This information gives me the incentive to work towards smaller doses of less hardcore exercise.
hit_cue2_q: That ultra processed foods contain more useless calories than minimally processed foods, and cause significant health issues was not a surprise. I have always found that processed foods cause my entire system to feel badly. Soon after eating such foods I will have heartburn, stomach pangs, increased fatigue, and other uncomfortable feelings. Contrasting that to the energy and feelings of satisfaction and well-being after eating a large salad with lots of different fruits and vegetables, makes it clear which is the healthier option.
hit_cue3_q: Many people are suprised by how much they actually consume when they record their daily intake.​​​​​​​ And for some people this self monitoring is a vital piece of their health journey. For me, obsessing over every morsel is a detriment to my mental health and so I do not journal in this way.
hit_cue4_q: It is easy to calculate the GI of a serving by multiplying the foods GI value by the number of carbs, and then dividing that figure by 100. This information is not something I will use as I am not a math minded person. I would much rather simply look up this information on a chart if I have a need of the numbers. But it was interesting to know how the number is actually determined.
hit_cue5_q: The Traffic Light Eating Plan suggests a diet that is high in low calorie foods like vegetables, fruits, and lean protein and dairy, This is common knowledge and the basis of nearly all diets I have ever explored. I have not heard of the particular diet before, but it is basically common sense eating.
hit_cue6_q: According to the presented information, people tend to eat more when presented with a large variety, so it is better to limit choices.​​​​​​​ I strongly disagree with this conclusion. I have always found that having a choice of foods that I can use to make a pleasing me leaves me far more satisfied. Being more satisfied by what I had for a meal means that I am less likely to go in search of additional foods or dessert.
hit_cue7_q: Strengthening exercises can result in better health results such as losing fat mass and lower blood sugar. Prior to living with chronic pain and other issues, I lifted weights with a trainer daily. I was healthier, in many different ways, than any other time in my life. I had always focused on aerobic exercises until that time. I am now a huge advocate of weight work and strengthening exercises.

eft_cue_1month_q: In about 1 month, I am looking forward to giving my mother a gift for Mother's Day. It's a nice spring day, and I'm giving her a new vacuum. She's happy with her gift, too. We're at home or at a nice restaurant to commemorate the occasion.
eft_cue_3month_q: In about 3 months, I am taking a trip to Washington, D.C. I enjoyed the road trip and am now enjoying the buildings and historical landmarks. I am walking around with my parents and sisters. I am enjoying the weather and the sights.
eft_cue_6month_q: In about 6 months, I am treating myself to ice cream. It's still a little warm outside, so the ice cream is a welcome addition to my day. It tastes sweet and has a nice crunch from the add-ins. I'm alone, but it's okay. I'm enjoying my own company as I eat.
eft_cue_1year_q: In about 1 year, I am at my own home relaxing. It's decorated just how I like with music playing at just the right volume. It looks like it's going to rain, which is nice. I'm alone, but that's okay. I'm watching something funny or playing a video game, and I'm having a good time.
eft_cue_3year_q: In about 3 years, I am hanging out with my fiance. He's on my arm, and we're walking in a pretty place like New Orleans. We're chatting about nothing in particular as we go, and we're happy to be together.
eft_cue_5year_q: In about 5 years, I am playing the latest The Legend of Zelda game. I'm playing it alone, as you do, and fighting off some ferocious monsters as I explore the beautiful kingdom of Hyrule. My husband's watching me play and helping where he can. I'm enjoying the adventure and am happy to share it with my loved one.
eft_cue_10year_q: In about 10 years, I am taking a trip to Ireland. I'm with my husband, and we're exploring the hills and bogs of the Emerald Isle. It's green, it's cool, and it's lovely. We enjoy a day out in nature and have dinner in Dublin, where we end up feeling nice and fed.

hit_cue1_q: I learned that doing short bursts of exercise or moderate activity can be just as good a steady vigorous exercise. This information gave me hope that I am in better shape than most people my age simply because I do a lot of short exercising when I clean up, play with my dogs, cut the grass, etc. I don't need to go to the gym when I can get moderate exercise at home.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that ultra processed foods are high in fat and sugars. This information makes me think about looking at the back of packaging more carefully. I didn't even know that these processed foods make you eat even more!
hit_cue3_q: I learned that self monitoring increases my awareness of how many calories I am actually consuming.​​​​​​​ I thought about this, would this make me feel good by looking back at all I've consumed? I think it would be helpful,  more self awareness. I do know some people that keep apps that track their intake.
hit_cue4_q: I learned that food have different GI values which affect me. this was very interesting. I will look up the values later, I'd like at least know the values of the food I eat.  Some foods would be obvious, but it's good to know.
hit_cue5_q: I learned that I should consume lower density foods in order to feel satiated. I never realized how food takes up space in your body. I do question if I would eat lower density foods that I would feel full but the fullness wouldn't last as long as a higher density food. I will check on that since it's interesting.
hit_cue6_q: I learned to use variety in meal planning focusing on low density food.​​​​​​​ This information makes me want to put more effort into providing multiple tasty low density foods. Typically my meals revolve around the meat and a side but I don't really focus on the side dish being exciting. I will start.
hit_cue7_q: I learned that strengthening exercises reduces my weight. i already knew this but need to implement this as I age to keep me strong.

hit_cue1_q: I learned that some benefits can happen immediately for brain health after physical activity. I am now aware of how quickly these benefits can occur. It made me think about how it can be important to exercise when some of the benefits show up immediately after which is interesting to me. I think this information is useful for almost anyone because it is important to be physically active to some degree. The information made me feel more interested in forming an exercise routine and engaging in physical activities more often.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that the average American diet contains high amounts of calories coming from ultra-processed foods. This isn't too surprising knowing how bad the average American diet is. The information is important when one considers their health and to know that sometimes the average is not a great indicator of good health. I am more interested in eating a healthy diet with less ultra-processed foods.
hit_cue3_q: I learned that it can be beneficial to monitor food intake more in order to make better decisions. It makes sense that this would lead to better outcomes. I think this information is useful for people that want to manage their weight and health. It makes me want to be more aware of my food decisions.​​​​​​​
hit_cue4_q: I learned how to calculate the glycemic load of food. It is interesting to know this so I can make better informed eating decisions. I think it can be useful to anyone tracking their food and diet. It made me curious to know more about the glycemic load of certain foods I consume.
hit_cue5_q: I learned about the Traffic Light Eating Plan. It was interesting to know about how this type of plan manages diet. I think it could be useful for certain people wanting this type of plan. It made me want to know a bit more information about how people feel about it.
hit_cue6_q: I learned about how variety can impact food decisions.​​​​​​​ It makes sense that it would impact it in certain ways. I think this information is useful to most people that make different dietary decisions. The information made me want to consider what I'm eating more.
hit_cue7_q: I learned about what the American Diabetes Association recommends for strength activities that people with diabetes can do. It made me understand more about how people with diabetes can still be physically active. I think this information is useful for people that either have diabetes or know people with the condition. The information made me feel more aware that people with diabetes can still do strengthening exercises.

comments: I found this survey to be very thought provoking and personally useful to me.
hit_cue1: Shorts spouts of moderate to vigorous activity can lessen anxiety, improve sleep, and improve cognitive function. I am aware of this information, yet have forgotten about it over time. This information made me think about considering including a brisk exercise like stair climbing into my daily routine. This information will be useful for me and others like me. The information made me feel more aware of simple things or routines that can improve my health.
hit_cue2: Moderation is key when consuming ultra processed foods. This information made me think about my bulging waist line, and the fact that I over indulge in my consumption of ultra-processed foods. This information is useful for anyone, frankly. This information made me feel a bit embarassed abolut my lack of self control when it comes to eating the wrong types of foods.
hit_cue3: The goal of self-monitoring is to increase your awareness of the behaviors that lead to weight loss.​​​​​​​ I thought about how lazy I have been, not employing this simple, yet effective weight loss strategy. This information can be useful for anyone who really wants to lose weight. The information made me feel empowered to take a positive step toward weight loss.
hit_cue4: The glycemic index (GI) of a food refers to how much change in blood glucose you can expect from eating that food, and it ranges from 0 to 100. The information made me think about my diabetes, and how this knowledge can help me manage it effectively with the help of my medication. This information is useful for anyone; however, I think it is most useful for those who have pre Diabetes or who are diabetic. The information made me feel like I can be part of my treatment for my diabetes.
hit_cue5: Foods like vegetables, fruits, lean proteins, and low fat dairy products tend to have lower energy densities. This information made me think about practical ways to control my weight. I thought of the famous "Mediterranean Diet". I think that this information is useful for anyone interested in maintaining a healthy balanced diet, without having to sacrifice on taste. The information made me feel inspired to go to the supermarket and pick out some new meats and vegetables!
hit_cue6: I learned that when arranging your food environment at home or at work, it can be helpful to increase the variety of satiating, low-energy dense foods (e.g., vegetables, fruits, lean protein, low-fat diary) while decreasing the variety of high-energy foods (fatty proteins, full-fat diary, sweets, oils).​​​​​​​ This information made me feel like this is a change I can make easily on my own. This information is useful for anyone, frankly. The information made me feel like it is time for me to make a positive change in my eating habits.
hit_cue7: I learned that Strengthening exercises can result in better blood sugar control, reduced insulin resistance, decreased fat mass, lower blood pressure, and increased muscle strength, and is recommended with people (like me) that struggle with diabetes. The information made me think about the feasibility of me engaging in strength or muscle toning because I suffer from extreme physical illness, and I am not sure that I am capable of doing these recommended exercises. This information is probably useful for most people. The information made me feel a bit nervous and worried about attempting such exercises.

hit_cue1_q: I learned that moderate-vigorous activity can relieve one of stress, improve sleep, and helps improve cognitive functions such as memory, planning ability, and attention. I need to start applying some of these tactics in my every day life. This information can be used everyone no matter how young or old. I feel better informed after taking part in this study!
hit_cue2_q: I learned that a majority of the calories the average American intakes is from ultra-oasturized foods and empty calories. It is beneficial for everyone to monitor calorie intake to ensure they are getting the most out of their foods.
hit_cue3_q: I learned that self-monitoring calorie intake can be an inspiration to continue eating healthier.​​​​​​​ Self monitoring can not only help improve the nutrients you intake, but it can also assist in budgeting. More money means more opportunity to buy healthy snacks!
hit_cue4_q: I learned that the glycemic index can give you an idea of how much change in blood glucose you can expect from eating that food. hit_cue5_q: I learned that limiting foods with high energy density is beneficial to maintaining weightloss and healthy eating habits. High energy density foods take up the same amount of space in our stomachs as lower desity levels.
hit_cue6_q: I learned that people tend to consume less calories when variety is reduced in a meal.​​​​​​​ If you are having a hard time consuming less, you can adjust the types of foods being eaten to better manage the healthy calories from the empty ones.
hit_cue7_q: I learned that strengthening exercises have many health benefits such as lower blood pressure and increased muscle strength. This is especially important for old people who may not have the energy they used to have to burn calories through vigorous activity.

hit_cue1_q: It only takes ten minutes a day to have a positive impact on your health with regards to exercise.  This information was somewhat familiar to me but really made me think about how I could be more active in my own life. This information would be great for people who are mostly sedentary or worried about how to get started with exercise. I'd say this information made me feel energized and inspired.
hit_cue2_q: Ultra-processed food should be consumed with moderation as they contain a lot of calories and can raise blood sugar and fat levels. I always knew that ultra-processed weren't that good for you but it made me think more in depth about just how bad they can be. People who eat a lot of snack foods would benefit from this information, and it makes me feel rather dejected.
hit_cue3_q: Recording how much you eat helps inform you and lets you make better eating choices in the future.​​​​​​​ I was aware of this technique and it made me think about times in my life where I had used it. This is helpful for literally everyone and it made me feel in control.
hit_cue4_q: Foods that are high on the glycemic index can strongly affect a person's blood glucose levels. I wasn't aware of this in a detailed level and it makes me think about people in my life who struggle with diabetes. This info would be good for both those with diabetes and those at risk. It makes me feel sort of sad.
hit_cue5_q: Avoiding high calorie and high energy density foods and eating a diet of lean proteins and low in fat can help with hunger and feelings of satiety. This was somewhat new to me but some parts were known so it made me feel sort of amused but also inquisitive. It made me also think about how I could apply it to my life. And it fits into my existing knowledge as I always knew that eating a diet rich in vegetables was good for you. I think everyone could benefit from knowing this.
hit_cue6_q: People tend to eat more foods when there is a lot of variety and this can be used to your advantage by having the same high calorie foods so you don't overindulge.​​​​​​​ I have to say I was surprised by this and felt taken aback. I never knew about this phenomenon and it made me worry that I was falling victim to it in my own life. Everyone should know about this and it should be taught in health classes.
hit_cue7_q: Diabetics can greatly benefit from strengthening exercises as it can help lower blood pressure and help with regulating blood sugar levels. This knowledge amplifies and adds to what I know about diabetes. I am and still continue to be largely in the dark when it comes to the disease but it made me think about how I could use it in my own life to manage my risks. Though overall this information is more useful for people suffering from diabetes, it still made me feel empowered and happy.

hit_tag1_q: I learned that moderate to vigorous activity can improve brain health.
hit_tag2_q: I learned that ultra processed foods should be eaten in close moderation.
hit_tag3_q: Self monitoring behaviors such as recording what you eat and drink each day can increase your behaviors that lead to weight loss.
hit_tag4_q: The glycemic index (GI) of a food refers to how much change in blood glucose you can expect from eating that food.
hit_tag5_q: A big part of the way we experience hunger and fullness is related to how much physical space the food we have eaten takes up in our stomach.
hit_tag6_q: People tend to consume less calories when variety is reduced in a meal, or when presented with the same foods across time.
hit_tag7_q: The American Diabetes Association recommends that individuals with diabetes engage in 2-3 days of full-body muscle strengthening activities per week.
hit_cue1_q: I learned that moderate to vigorous activity can improve brain health. I'm not sure that I realized that physical activity was important to brain health. Too frequently I feel that I have a lapse in brain function so this causes me to pause and ponder this aspect. So, yes this information is useful for me and it makes me feel that I need to find a way to increase activity significantly.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that ultra processed foods should be eaten in close moderation. I think everybody is aware that processed foods are not good in large quantities. This makes me consider ways that I can decrease that type of food in my menu. Living alone can make it easy just to live on mostly processed foods because cooking fresh is no fun just for yourself.
hit_cue3_q: Self monitoring behaviors such as recording what you eat and drink each day can increase your behaviors that lead to weight loss.​​​​​​​ I am very poor at keeping records of any kind so this would be a challenge albeit interesting. I actually would love to see this in black and white and over time. This makes me feel challenged to consider doing because it does interest me.
hit_cue4_q: The glycemic index (GI) of a food refers to how much change in blood glucose you can expect from eating that food. I've known a small bit about glycemic index but not enough to put it to any use. It makes me realize how uninformed I am and how this could seriously benefit my blood sugar levels.
hit_cue5_q: A big part of the way we experience hunger and fullness is related to how much physical space the food we have eaten takes up in our stomach. I need to do some research on higher energy dense foods that will help me better control hunger.
hit_cue6_q: People tend to consume less calories when variety is reduced in a meal, or when presented with the same foods across time.​​​​ This I think I know intuitively but I did not realize the "science" b​​ehind it. And I am definitely going to start doing more of what it says.​
hit_cue7_q: The American Diabetes Association recommends that individuals with diabetes engage in 2-3 days of full-body muscle strengthening activities per week. This makes me realize that I need all kinds of increased activity. I'm thinking that I might need a trainer initially to get me started. But there are so many benefits to increased muscle mass that could benefit me tremendously.

hit_cue1: I learned that moderate to vigorous activity can improve brain health. I'm not sure that I realized that physical activity was important to brain health. Too frequently I feel that I have a lapse in brain function so this causes me to pause and ponder this aspect. So, yes this information is useful for me and it makes me feel that I need to find a way to increase activity significantly.
hit_cue2: I learned that ultra processed foods should be eaten in close moderation. I think everybody is aware that processed foods are not good in large quantities. This makes me consider ways that I can decrease that type of food in my menu. Living alone can make it easy just to live on mostly processed foods because cooking fresh is no fun just for yourself.
hit_cue3: Self monitoring behaviors such as recording what you eat and drink each day can increase your behaviors that lead to weight loss.​​​​​​​ I am very poor at keeping records of any kind so this would be a challenge albeit interesting. hit_cue4: The glycemic index (GI) of a food refers to how much change in blood glucose you can expect from eating that food. hit_cue5: A big part of the way we experience hunger and fullness is related to how much physical space the food we have eaten takes up in our stomach. I need to do some research on higher energy dense foods that will help me better control hunger.
hit_cue6: People tend to consume less calories when variety is reduced in a meal, or when presented with the same foods across time.​​​​ This I think I know intuitively but I did not realize the "science" b​​ehind it. And I am definitely going to start doing more of what it says.​
hit_cue7: The American Diabetes Association recommends that individuals with diabetes engage in 2-3 days of full-body muscle strengthening activities per week. eft_cue_1month_q:
In about 1 month, I am going to my sister's house for the annual crawfish boil. I am placing the dish I prepared on the table and shoving others aside to fit it in between. I'm appreciating all of the food that's available. I'm with Mom and three of my four sister's and their husbands, and all of the friends of my sister's who have been attending the event for years.

I'm checking out the kiddie pool that holds the cleaned crawfish, and telling them that they will be tasty. I'm enjoying watching everyone have a good time and eating and drinking. I'm smiling while I catch up with anyone I haven't seen since the prior year's boil.

I'm sipping a glass of wine while I eat the plate that I filled with side dishes, and thinking of how I can steal as many desserts to take home as possible.
eft_cue_3month_q:
In about 3 months, I am at our beach house for the 4th of July. I am walking into the house and setting some supplies down before I walk the structure and inspect for anything that needs addressed before the rest of the family arrives. I'm smelling a bit of musty odor from the drains as they have not had water run in them for a few months.

I'm greeting my sisters and their husbands, and grabbing items from their overloaded arms as the enter the house. I'm instructing them all where they will sleep, and giving two of the couples keys to the house next door where they will stay.

I'm feeling great that we are all together for the evening, and anticipating the fireworks display that surrounds us every year. I'm thinking of how lucky we all are.
eft_cue_6month_q:
In about 6 months, I am at a dear friend's for her 65th birthday party. I am standing in her kitchen drinking a vodka tonic with lime and teasing her about her age because she's a whole week older than me. 

I'm greeting guests as they arrive and hugging the ones that I know and introducing myself to the ones I don't. I'm pointing them to the sunroom where the party is set up and already progressing. I'm suggesting they all hit the bar for a cocktail and smiling as they enter the room that's decorated with black balloons and banners.
eft_cue_1year_q:
In about 1 year, I am in Ohio for the 5th anniversary of my boyfriends death for a memorial in his honor at the fire department. Though a somber event, it has been five years and this is a celebration of Paul's life and I think of it that way.

I'm greeting people at the event and sharing in laughter about whatever antics they bring up about Paul. I'm hugging my grandkids whom I haven't seen in a few years and commenting on how grown up they all are. I'm teasing all six of them by calling them all by the wrong name on purpose.

I'm enjoying the company of Paul's siblings as we always loved each other as though we were siblings ourselves. I'm enjoyong hearing his sister discussing 'what's new on the farm'.

I'm smiling, remembering how much Paul loved me.
eft_cue_3year_q:
In about 3 years, I am at a special dinner for my mom's 90th birthday. I'm at her favorite restaurant with Mom and the rest of my siblings and my niece and nephew and their small children. I'm joking with my brother about how white his hair has gotten since the last time I saw him.

I'm looking at everyone sitting at the extended table having fun and enjoying the great food, and eating my delicious fish tacos that I haven't had in a few months. I'm wondering how many more birthdays my saint-of-a-mom will have left, and vowing to spend more time with her doing things we love like going to the museum and spending time at the beach.
eft_cue_5year_q: In about 5 years, I am playing pranks on my grandkids for April Fool's Day. I am in Ohio since it's been a few years since I've been here, and none of us are getting any younger. I'm telling off-color stories to my two now adult grandsons, and laughing hysterically at their reactions while knowing the stories are not entirely true.
eft_cue_10year_q: In about 10 years, I am filing my taxes that show a huge return coming my way. I'm by myself at the post office standing in line waiting for my turn at the counter to put my tax document into the mail. I'm by myself, and smiling ear-to-ear knowing how much money I'm getting back.

hit_cue1: I learned that small amounts of exercise can immediately reduce short term anxiety. This does differ from what I've heard in the past. I always thought that exercise needed to take place for longer periods of time to be beneficial. I think the information is useful for everyone who finds it difficult to fit exercise into their daily lives. It made me feel hopeful that I could incorporate easy exercises into my daily routine.
hit_cue2: 58% of calories in the average American diet come from ultra processed foods. I didn't have any existing knowledge of this topic but I did find it interesting that the number is so high. I think the information is useful to everyone and might make people think twice about putting certain foods on their plate. It made me feel determined to eat a little better.
hit_cue3: Knowing how many calories you consume can make it easier to choose better food or activity choices in the future​​​​​​​. This fit into my existing knowledge fairly well. I think this information is useful for people who are trying to set goals for themselves to better their health. It made me feel like I was making good choices in my life already.
hit_cue4: The GI of a food refers to how much change in blood glucose you can expect from eating that food. I didn't know anything about GI before reading this. It made me wonder about my own glucose levels and how they may be fixed using this information. I think this information is useful for everyone who might be facing GI issues. It made me feel a little confused that I've never heard of this before.
hit_cue5: The energy density of a food is the amount of calories the food has in a given volume. I hadn't thought about the density of my food before. It makes me wonder about my own food choices and if they're dense in the right way. I think this is useful for everyone who is trying to find a new way of thinking about their diets. It made me feel determined to make better choices regarding this information.
hit_cue6: It can be helpful to increase the variety of satiating, low-energy dense foods while decreasing the variety of high energy foods. ​​​​​​​I have not thought much about the varitey of my foods. I think this is a very interesting way to think about what we put on our plates. Variety can help a lot of people with diets who might be sick of eating the same foods over and over again. It made me feel hopeful that when I eat healthy foods it doesn't have to be boring.
hit_cue7: Strengthening exercises can result in better blood sugar control, reduced insulin resistance, decreaesd fat mass, lower blood pressure and increased muscle strength. I think the information is useful for everyone. It made me feel hopeful that this form of exercise would fix a lot of my problems.

hit_cue1_q: I learned that even small amounts of exercise not only improves general health, but also brain/mental health. Reading this made me think of how bad my own health/mental health is, and how maybe exercise could help. I was aware of the physical benefits as well as the mental/brain benefits, but I didn't know the effects could be felt so fast. This information should be useful to everyone who's able to exercise, of any age. With this information, I felt it's possible to make small changes to my health.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that 58% of the diet of an average American contains ultra-processed foods, and eliminating them all probably won't happen. I'm not sure if the ultra-processed foods that this article is referring to are regular processed foods that have just been named to increase people's awareness of just how unhealthy they are. I knew most of the information related to processed foods in this article, for example, how unhealthy they are, and how they don't tend to make you feel full. I was unaware of the statistic about just how much processed foods Americans consume. Reading this made me realize I'm not the only one eating unhealthy, and it's something that should change for us, but I'm not sure that it will. It takes individual effort, although we can of course support one another. This information would be useful for young kids who are learning about nutrition, because I feel most adults know most of these things already. I kind of feel that it's a little pointless to overly focus so much on nutrition and eating healthy, since unhealthy foods can't be avoided in this country. I feel like we should just try our best to eat healthy and not obsess over it.
hit_cue3_q: I learned that monitoring your food intake is similar to keeping a budget, and can help you make more informed choices in the future.​​​​​​​ However, I feel that most people already know this information already. The whole point of monitoring food intake and physical activity is so you can get a better handle on your health and hopefully make better and more informed choices that will improve your health. I thought of younger people and people around my age who use their phones and fitness trackers/watches to try and lose weight or help monitor health conditions. Technology can be useful and it isn't all a waste of time, and using it for this is a good example. This information would be good for kids/young people, or someone just starting out to improve their health. I feel like it could possibly help me with my health/losing weight, if I paid more attention to what I eat and how much activity I do.
hit_cue4_q: I learned that you can calculate the glycemic load of food by multiplying the GI value by the number of carbs in one serving, then dividing by 100. Most of this information was new to me, such as the previous information I mentioned, as well as the different GI ranges of various foods, and just what numbers constitute a low/moderate/high GI. Reading this made me wonder how the food I regularly eat affects my glycemic index, and how close I could be to getting diabetes. This information is useful to both diabetics and non-diabetics, including people who are concerned they could develop diabetes. I felt somewhat scared after reading this, because I know I don't eat right, and was already tested for diabetes long ago when I was younger when my blood sugar was found to be high one day (the doctor  thankfully said I was fine, however).
hit_cue5_q: I learned that to find the energy density of a food product, you take the calories and divide by the weight. Although I knew the gist of what this article was saying, the whole concept of energy density sounds like a new (or new-to-me) rephrasing of what people already know: that calorie-rich/high-fat foods are bad, and lower-calorie/low-fat foods are good, generally (apart from good fats). It made me think of how people diet and how useless they are. It's better just to eat well. This information might be useful to teens/younger people. I felt tired reading this though, because I already know this information and have heard it many times.
hit_cue6_q: I learned that people tend to consume fewer calories when food variety is reduced, or when they have to eat the same foods over time.​​​​​​​ The general point of this article doesn't really sit with my own personal experience though, because I can overeat foods that I eat on a regular basis. So I'm not sure if I'm an outlier, or this information just isn't accurate. It made me think about how my eating habits are bad and how much junk food I tend to consume. This information might be useful to someone who's tried to lose weight in other ways, but was unsuccessful. For me, this information didn't make much sense though, and if I were looking to lose weight/eat healthier, I'd try another resource.
hit_cue7_q: I learned that strength training is recommended to diabetics because it helps reduce insulin resistance and improves blood sugar control, along with other health benefits. I knew that it was good in general, but the benefit to diabetics was new to me. I also didn't know that strength training is recommended to older adults, since it can actually lower the risk from falls. It makes me realize strength training isn't just for the young and healthy. I think anyone of any age could benefit from reading this, including diabetics and older adults. I felt armed with more useful knowledge after reading this.

eft_cue_1month_q: In about 1 month, I am watching the NASCAR race at Kansas Speedway from home. I am texting with friends about what is happening in the race and we share our predictions. I am eating pizza which I've held off all week for. I'm excited to see how my favorite drivers are doing.
eft_cue_3month_q: In about 3 months, I am watching the first NASCAR street race in Chicago from my house. I am listening intently to the description of the course to see which parts will likely bring action. I am watching how my driver is doing in the course of the race. I'm learning about the strategy of the race teams as the race goes on. I'm texting with friends who are also watching the race to see how their drivers do and we are comparing notes about what we think. I am really absorbing all the information I can both from hearing and seeing since this is a new course. I am rooting for my driver to do well.
eft_cue_6month_q: In about 6 months, I am watching NASCAR race to see which drivers will make it into the final eight of the playoffs. I am hoping that my driver is still in the hunt. I am listening closely to any strategy calls for fuel or tire wear that may affect the race. I have nervous excited energy for all the drivers because it's the playoffs. I'm texting with friends who are also pulling for different drivers in the race.
eft_cue_1year_q: In about 1 year, I am watching the season opening race of IndyCar at St. Petersburg at my home. Because it's the start of a fresh new season it feels exciting and also like a homecoming. I am listening to the announcers talk about who is likely to do well in the race based on qualifying. As always, I'm trying to learn more about the sport's strategy through commentators and team communications. I like that anything can happen during the race to help or hurt a driver's chances.
eft_cue_3year_q: In about 3 years, I am truly enjoying celebrating my birthday. I am with friends (both new and old) and it feels different because I'm full of optimism about feeling alive and being alive. We are eating fun festive foods like Mexican and enjoying each other's company.
eft_cue_5year_q: In about 5 years, I am enjoying Easter Sunday with a group of friends. We are car camping in Baja California at a hot spring and making the most ridiculous gourmet food to eat in the wilderness. We are in high spirits and the weather is clear and warm. We relax in the hot tub made of stones that the spring is pumped into and sleep under the stars.
eft_cue_10year_q: In about 10 years, I am watching the NASCAR race at Talladega with a group of friends. We pick cars and drivers to cheer for even if it's just based on the design of the car wrap. We splurge and eat food like fried calamari and cheese dips because it's Talladega. Every time there is a wreck we all jump up and yell, "They're wrecking! They're wrecking!".

I'm texting with friends who are also pulling for different drivers in the race.
eft_cue1year: In about 1 year, I am watching the season opening race of IndyCar at St. Petersburg at my home. Because it's the start of a fresh new season it feels exciting and also like a homecoming. I am listening to the announcers talk about who is likely to do well in the race based on qualifying. As always, I'm trying to learn more about the sport's strategy through commentators and team communications. I like that anything can happen during the race to help or hurt a driver's chances.
eft_cue3year: In about 3 years, I am truly enjoying celebrating my birthday. I am with friends (both new and old) and it feels different because I'm full of optimism about feeling alive and being alive. We are eating fun festive foods like Mexican and enjoying each other's company.
eft_cue5year: In about 5 years, I am enjoying Easter Sunday with a group of friends. We are car camping in Baja California at a hot spring and making the most ridiculous gourmet food to eat in the wilderness. We are in high spirits and the weather is clear and warm. We relax in the hot tub made of stones that the spring is pumped into and sleep under the stars.
eft_cue10year: In about 10 years, I am watching the NASCAR race at Talladega with a group of friends. We pick cars and drivers to cheer for even if it's just based on the design of the car wrap. We splurge and eat food like fried calamari and cheese dips because it's Talladega. Every time there is a wreck we all jump up and yell, "They're wrecking! They're wrecking!".

hit_tag1_q: One does not have to exercise a lot of time each day to reap the benefits that exercise provides.
hit_tag2_q: One should keep consumption of ultra-processed foods to a bare minimum.
hit_tag3_q: It pays to keep track of how much a person eats, drinks, and exercises so better adjustments can be made.
hit_tag4_q: Blood glucose is affected by carbohydrate intake and food ranking on the GI index.
hit_tag5_q: One should strive for a diet rich in high density energy and fewer calories.
hit_tag6_q: The proper low variety combination of high and low density energy foods help with weight loss.
hit_tag7_q: Doing full-body muscle strengthening exercises helps the health in many ways.
hit_cue1_q: It has been said before that bouts of small increments of strenuous exercise are just as beneficial as spending hours at a gym. One does not have to exercise a lot of time each day to reap the benefits that exercise provides.
hit_cue2_q: One should keep consumption of ultra-processed foods to a bare minimum.  Most snacks and sweets fall into the ultra category and should not be consumed too often.  This is helpful for persons with diabetes and those trying to lose weight.
hit_cue3_q: It pays to keep track of how much a person eats, drinks, and exercises so better adjustments can be made.​​​​​​​  It can be likened to keeping a budget, only this includes food and exercise intake.  One can see what results are obtainable by keeping such records.
hit_cue4_q: Blood glucose is affected by carbohydrate intake and food ranking on the GI index.  This is especially important for those with diabetic issues, as well as for anyone else trying to keep their blood sugar under control.  This preventive measure could stop the onset of future conditions and diseases.
hit_cue5_q: One should strive for a diet rich in high density energy and fewer calories.  If a person can fill up on high-energy, nutritious foods, this would go a long way towards better health and weight control.
hit_cue6_q: A large variety of food items makes a person want to eat more; that's only natural, to want to sample an array of great-looking and tasty foods. The proper low variety combination of high and low density energy foods help with weight loss.​​​​​​​
hit_cue7_q: Doing full-body muscle strengthening exercises helps the health in many ways.  Stronger bones and muscles, better sleep, better metabolism, and many other benefits can be had by practicing the exercises.  It is especially beneficial for seniors, who will tend to lose muscle strength and mass as they age.

eft_cue_1month_q: In about 1 month, I am sitting in chuch at a sunday morning worship service.  The praise band is playing music while the lead singer encourages the congregation to join in. This activity is starting at 10:30 am and continues until 12:00 PM (sometimes a bit longer) Following the Praise section of the service, the Pastor will preach a sermon from the Bible about how we will need to live.
eft_cue_3month_q: In about 3 months, I am at my Urologists office undergoing a biopsy on my Prostrate.  There are three of us in the room, me, the Urologist and his techniciam who runs the computer. They are sticking a probe with a camera and some kind of a clipper into my anus. When the Dr. is ready to take a sample a loud sound fills the room followed by a pinch inside me.  I am at the VA hospital closest to my house.
eft_cue_6month_q: In about 6 months, I am at an appointment with my Dermatologist to have my body scanned for cancer that is recuring.  Just the two of us are here.  This scan is being done with his eyes.  First he has asked me how I am feeling and if anything is changed.  Then I will disrobe almost completely.  He is looking me over, up and down, front and back.  Fortunately I again seem to be cancer free.
eft_cue_1year_q: In about 1 year, I am celebragting my 51st anniversary with my wife. Just the two of use are here, well, there are other patrons of this restaurant and the waite staff.  I am thinking back to one year ago when the offered times in a survey did not allow for my listing our 50th anniversary to celebrate with you.  This restaurant is a bit pricier than the ones we usually go to, but it is really nice.  Earlier today I gave my wife 51 red roses which she was very pleased with.
eft_cue_3year_q: In about 3 years, I am celebrating my wife's 72nd birthday with her.  We both have aged some, but she still looks very much like when I first met her.  We both are quite changed from what we used to be.  This is primarily due to our faith in Christ and our living day by day for Him.
eft_cue_5year_q: In about 5 years, I am preparing to file my Federal Income Tax Papers, which I do joyfully since the Bible says, "render unto Ceaser....." hit_cue1_q: I learned that while it was previously thought that exercise had to be at least 10 minutes to have a health impact, it has been found that even brief bouts of exercise can improve health. I remembering reading something similar to this recently, so it was not entriely new information but it confirmed what I had seen before. The information made me think about how it is easier to get in beneficial exercise if done in smaller bouts. This info may be useful for people who struggle to exercise or feel like it's pointless for them to try because doing a long exercise session is too hard. The information made me feel hopeful.
hit_cue2_q: I learned that ultra-processed foods have health risks. I already knew this information, though not the specific percentages of the American diet. The information made me think about how I enjoy ultra-processed food. It may be useful for people who are unaware of the health risks with ultraprocessed food. It made me feel sad and ashamed.
hit_cue3_q: I learned that some self-monitoring techniques are using an app and taking regular weight measurements.​​​​​​​ I was already aware of the information presented in the paragraph. It made me think about people who often use these techniques in eating disorders. The information might be helpful for people who have very little awareness or knowledge about weight loss techniques. It made me feel angry.
hit_cue4_q: I have learned that the term glycemic load is the glycemic index of the foods consumed in one meal multiplied by the number of carbs in the food, divided by 100. This information complements what I already knew about the glycemic index. The information made me think about the glycceminc loads of my meals. I think the information could be useful for anyone trying to lower or control their blood sugar. The information made me feel mildly ashamed of my food choices and preferences.
hit_cue5_q: I learned that part of the way we experience hunger and fullness is realted to how much physical space the food we have eaten takes up in our stomach. This information slightly contradicts my understanding of hunger/fullness signals. I thought the brain could process the calories of food to some degree before it is digested, but as I type that I realize it doesn't really make sense. The info made me think about what else informs the brain of our fullness. The info is probably useful for people who want to eat less but struggle with feeling hungry when they eat less. The information made me feel a little skeptical, resistant and ashamed.
hit_cue6_q: I learned that variety of food can make people eat more​​​​​​​. This info seemed antithetical to my understanding of healthy eating because a varied diet is a good thing. The information made me think about how it is encouraging people to restrict their eating further by limiting the variety and that this is the opposite of how parents are advised to present food to children (healthy or unhealthy - to be neutral to a child's interest in unhealthy food as well) This info may be useful for people who want to lose weight. The info made me feel resentful.

This info is useful for diabetic people who want to know how to better control their diabetes. It made me feel pressured and ashamed.

hit_cue2_q: I learned that ultra-processed foods have more fats, calories and are less nutritious when compared to unprocessed or less processed foods. hit_cue3_q: I learned that self-monitoring is a good way to track how much off and what you are eating and drinking everyday which can help you make more informed food choices. hit_cue4_q: I learned that the glycemic index lets you know how much the food you eat or drink will affect your blood glucose. it made me realize i didn't know how the glycemic index worked and made me think about how I still have a lot to learn about the food i eat. hit_cue5_q: I learned that low and high energy dense foods take up the same amount of space in our stomach but low dense foods have few calories. hit_cue6_q: I learned that limiting your access to high-energy foods while increasing access and variety to low-energy dense foods leads to less calories being consumed.​​​​​​​ Reading this made me feel that I'm making poor food choices while also thinking about what I can do to change my relationship with food. This is useful since i want to add more variety to my diet while also being healthy. This let me know that I have made some better choices when it comes to food but i still have a lot to work on and that variety is really the key of not getting bored and giving up.
hit_cue7_q: I learned strengthening exercises can have many positive effects on your overall health like lowering your blood pressure, increased muscle strength and lowering your fat mass. eft_cue_1month_q: In about 1 month, I am at the mall shopping.  I am with my brother Clifford at Northeast Mall.  We are shopping for both a birthday present and a Mother's day present for our mom.  We have found two wonderful gifts each for our mom.
eft_cue_3month_q: In about 3 months, I am at a birthday party for my three kittens.  Me, my mother, and my brother are throwing a birthday party for our three kittens.  Their names are Count Milo, Oreo and Phoenix.  I am giving them special treats to eat and we are all playing with them with new toys.  We are laughing, taking pictures of their antics, and truly enjoying the moment.
eft_cue_6month_q: In about 6 months, I am watching a scary movie.  I am alone and watching a scary movie.  It is Friday October the 13th and I always watch a scary movie on any Friday the 13th.  I have my popcorn and junior mints and a six pack.  The movie is scary and hits just the right tone for the day.  I am quite content when it is done.
eft_cue_1year_q: In about 1 year, I am celebrating 100 lbs of weight lost.  My family is with me and we are having a special dinner of pizza.  We are all happy since each one of us is celebrating significant weight loss.  This one day will be our once a year cheat day!
eft_cue_3year_q: In about 3 years, I am running my first 10K.  I am at a park with thousands of other people waiting to start the 1st 10k race in my life.  It is a gloriously beautiful morning and the temperature is just right at 52 degrees.  The air is crisp, clean; and I fell invigorated and alive.
eft_cue_5year_q: In about 5 years, I am running my first half marathon.  I am in the downtown area of another big city in Texas.  There are thousands of other runners getting ready to start a half marathon.  I am excited to start as I have trained for weeks for this event and it is a huge milestone in my journey to health.
eft_cue_10year_q: In about 10 years, I am running my 10th marathon.  I am at the Boston Marathon running in the 13th mile.  I am content and at peace and thinking about all the good hard work I have put in to qualify for this event at age 60.  This is one of the capstones to my journey from near death to being healthy.
